After watching this video, I realized how foolish my previous views on China were. I've decided to plan my trip this year to China. I feel that if I don't go to China, I'll regret it for the rest of my life.

I was one of the tourists visiting the Great Wall that day, and I happened to see Speed’s group. I honestly didn’t know who they were at first, but after asking people around me, I found out that he is a famous YouTuber. I really liked the positive energy from the group and observed from a distance. However, in China, certain behaviors and etiquette are taken quite seriously, and some of their actions were considered rather impolite.
I was traveling with my family, but our experience that day wasn’t the best. The path up was already quite narrow and dangerous, yet Speed’s group arrived later and still pushed ahead, cutting in line. On top of that, his security team was rather rude, telling people to "get out of the way." My family and I had to cling to the wall just to make space for them.
I hope you can be a bit less on guard and have a better travel experience in China. Security here is very strict, with guards and surveillance cameras everywhere, so there’s no need to be overly cautious. People will naturally give you space because everyone wants to enjoy their trip. I truly appreciate you for sharing Chinese culture and cuisine with the world, but please also be mindful of shared spaces and keep your voice down a little. That way, both locals and tourists alike can have a more positive impression of you :)

Hey Speed,

I’m from China, and for the past two weeks, the most talked-about topic on the Chinese internet has been you. Previously, most people here didn’t know you, but now, many more do—welcome to China!

Many people, including myself, sincerely suggest that you find a more reliable translator. Seriously, the translators you've had so far have significantly lowered the professionalism of your team.

For example, the translator in Beijing—when you went for a haircut. The barber genuinely wanted to serve you, but they might not have had experience with your hairstyle and were concerned that cutting it might make it difficult to restore your braids. They were thinking in your best interest. However, the translator absurdly said that they found your hair dirty and messy. My goodness, that was a disaster.

Another example is the female translator at the Shaolin Temple in Henan. Your Shifu didn’t want to accept your payment because you connected through martial arts. He even told you in English, so you should have understood. But considering your enthusiasm, he added that if you insisted on giving something, you could buy some snacks for the children. His emotional intelligence was incredibly high—his last sentence both preserved your dignity and created a great opportunity for goodwill.

Yet, that female translator told you that you didn’t need to pay because the government had already covered the cost…

Honestly, honestly, honestly—so many of us watching were beyond frustrated. We sincerely, sincerely, sincerely urge you: please, please, please find a reliable translator.

Chinese people are not racially discriminatory. We love playful memes and slang, but never with offensive intent.
In everyday Mandarin, especially in Beijing, the word ‘那个’ (pronounced ‘nèi ge’) is one of the most common filler phrases, similar to saying ‘um’ or ‘that thing’ in English. For example:

‘Wait, I need… nèi ge… my phone!’

‘Where’s nèi ge… the remote control?’

However, due to its phonetic similarity to a certain English slur, Chinese netizens sometimes joke about it in lighthearted memes or puns. This is purely cultural wordplay and never meant to offend. We’re just having fun with language quirks!

Chinese humor often embraces linguistic coincidences, but we deeply respect all cultures and communities. If non-Chinese speakers misunderstand, we’re happy to clarify!"

But if you ever get the chance to explore Beijing's authentic local life - those hidden alleyway eateries, the street vendors flipping jianbing at dawn, the old-timers playing chess in hutong courtyards - you'd absolutely fall in love with this city. The real Beijing magic happens off-camera, in the sizzle of lamb skewers on a winter night or the fragrant steam of freshly brewed jasmine tea.
Psst... Many local creators now capture this vibe through carefully curated vlogs - a smart workaround that keeps things compliant while showing the city's true character.

I think the bodyguard seems to be really eager to do his job well, but that doesn't mean his behavior isn't reckless. However, he has ignored the basic etiquette in China. Firstly, it is indeed inappropriate to speak loudly in public places, including in a vehicle. This applies whether it's a big Chinese celebrity or a Chinese government official. Secondly, it's really not right to gather a crowd or ask other tourists to move aside on the Great Wall. Many people are not fans of Speed, and they won't harm Speed either. It's very difficult to find a Chinese person in China who would randomly attack passersby. Other tourists are just living their own lives. If you, Speed, are also reading this comment, you need to understand some of the basic etiquette of the Chinese people so that more Chinese audiences will like you, and don't exhibit impolite behavior. I don't mean to be offensive when I say this, but it's just that the culture in China is indeed a bit different from that in the United States.

Standing atop these ancient stone veins that pulse with twenty-two centuries of history, I trace my fingers along weathered battlements born in 221 BCE. These stones once vibrated with war drums and soldiers' battle cries, erected through dynasties' sweat and blood to shield civilization from northern storms. The same watchtowers that once blazed with warning fires now frame children's laughter echoing through maple leaves, their arrow slits transformed into viewfinders capturing cloud-draped mountains rolling toward the horizon.

Beneath my feet, the Great Wall's spine undulates like a dormant dragon petrified mid-guardian's vow. Its original purpose - that desperate human need to divide "us" from "them" through mortar and might - lies buried deeper than its own foundations. Today, pilgrims from every compass point climb not to conquer, but to marvel at how morning mist tenderly veils the same northern frontier that once sparked such dread.

The wind carries ghosts of both - drawn bowstrings and camera shutters, clashing steel and awestruck whispers. In this sacred overlap of timelines, I grasp how these stones now serve a nobler vigilance: not repelling invaders, but guarding humanity's fragile hope that one day, all borders might fade like morning dew, leaving only this eternal truth - that what we build to separate, time ultimately consecrates to unite.
